  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Augustus Hesse requests Deborah Weston to secure a certificate from Mr. Humphry, the selectman of &quot;my town&quot; [Weymouth, Mass.], so that Hesse can have a furlough of a few days. Hesse writes: &quot;I am content still I wish be mor[e] Content if I had bid you all---my Wife &amp; Child good bye---We are here all in our Battery old Soldiers.&quot; If any of the Weston family should come to the camp, Augustus Hesse would make it as comfortable as he could. He sends a message to his wife, Almira, and &quot;Kiss my little darling for me.&quot; It will take a month to get through all the manoeuvres which they have to learn in the artillery service.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Includes an envelope with the delivery address: Mrs. Almira Hesse, Care of Miss D. Weston, Weymouth Landing, Mass. The envelope has the image of a U.S. war flag.</subfield>
  </datafield>
